ce:section.ce:para:
In this article, highly red-emissive CDs (R-CDs) were successfully prepared from solvothermal treatment of o-phenylenediamine and sorbitol in ethanol, then we applied them to the field of veterinary drug detection (Scheme 1
                     ). To explore the structural characteristic of R-CDs, TEM characterization was performed. In Fig. 1
                     a, the R-CDs possess good dispersibility without obvious aggregation phenomenon. The inset picture in Fig. 1a exhibits the HRTEM image of a single CD, displaying the lattice spacing of 0.21 nm, which is assigned to (100) plane of graphitic carbon [34]. Moreover, the size distribution analysis reveals an average diameter of 4.36 nm of R-CDs (Fig. S1). XRD pattern of R-CDs exhibits a wide diffraction peak with 2θ values of 24° (Fig. 1b), which is assigned to the (002) plane of graphitization structure [35,36]. The Raman spectrum shown in Fig. 1c exhibits two obvious peaks centered at 1352 and 1595 cm−1, assigning to D and G bands, respectively, proving the formation of graphitization. Notably, the intensity of G band is stronger than that of D band, revealing the high quality of the graphitic structure of R-CDs [37]. In addition, the functional groups on R-CDs were explored. Fig. 1d shows the FT-IR spectrum of R-CDs, the absorptions appear at 3410, 3390, 2850, 1642, 1524 and 1480 cm−1 are assigned to the vibrations of N–H, O–H, C–H, CO/CN, CC and C–N = , respectively [19]. The above results indicate that the R-CDs might have sp2 graphitic domain along with abundant surface functional groups.
